I did this quick design to test the dissolving resin on our newly acquired 2X and for my daughter who attends Purdue to try and investment cast PLA. Things I have learned so far. Don't print PLA with the unit closed up. Print standing up not on its side. This was done in SW. Hardest part was finding a close font.

https://www.bing.com/images/search?view=detailV2&ccid=Fs3KIwjq&id=29817119F210955F1F423225B794C1B8A9AEA3ED&thid=OIP.Fs3KIwjq6wwbnQ6hGFgB1QEsDI&mediaurl=http%3a%2f%2fimages.fineartamerica.com%2fimages-medium-large-5%2fpurdue-university-block-p-project-statue-david-haskett.jpg&exph=600&expw=900&q=purdue+p+statue&simid=608045170560598898&selectedIndex=0&ajaxhist=0

This year I wanted to make a costume that was a little more original, and still went a long with my subtle side. So, I decided to create a Tony Stark costume! There are lots of Iron Man costumes out there, very well done I might add, but I haven't seen Tony Stark around much. So, here it is, my Arc Reactor, controlled by my phone, over Bluetooth. I wrote a very simple program to change colors using an app on my phone to switch through them.

Design:
I had seen other Arc Reactor prints in multiple pieces, and requiring assembly. I didn't want to do that with mine, I like simple, so I designed a one piece Arc Reactor in Autodesk Inventor, and painted it with some low cost paint from Walmart.

It prints flat, rotate it 90 degrees so it is laying down on the printer bed, and print with no support material. I like to design things to avoid support material when I can. I printed it using clear PLA, 1.75mm clear plastic. With clear plastic, it is important to print at 100% infill, so the light diffuses properly.

Electrical:
Arduino is awesome! I used a Bluno Beetle, programmed it using the Arduino IDE. For the LED lights I used 2 generic neopixel rings, a 12 Pixel RGB LED ring for the outer lights, and a 7 Pixel RGB LED ring for the inner core lights. It is all powered by a cheap power bank, 5 volts output.

Programming:
Here is the code I wrote, using the NeoPixel Library.
//

include

define strip_pin A2

define strip2_pin A1

define strip_count 7

define strip2_count 16

Adafruit_NeoPixel strip = Adafruit_NeoPixel(strip_count, strip_pin, NEO_RGB + NEO_KHZ800);
Adafruit_NeoPixel strip2 = Adafruit_NeoPixel(strip2_count, strip2_pin, NEO_RGB + NEO_KHZ800);
int neo_delay (500);
int showType = 0;
char switch_show;
int done = 0;

void neo_setup() {
strip.begin();
strip2.begin();
for(int i=0;i<strip_count;i++){
strip.setPixelColor(i, strip.Color(150,150,150));
strip.show();
delay(1);
}
for(int i=0;i<strip2_count;i++){
strip2.setPixelColor(i, strip2.Color(150,150,150));
strip2.show();
delay(1);
}
}

void setup() {
Serial.begin(115200);
neo_setup();
}

void loop() {
if (Serial.available()) {
switch_show = Serial.read();// add it to the inputString:
Serial.println(switch_show);
cycle_show();
}
}

void cycle_show() {
switch (switch_show) {
case 'a':
done = 0;
colors(0,0,0);
colors1(0,0,0);
break;
case 'b':
colors(0,0,150);
break;
case 'c':
colors(255,255,255);
break;
case 'd':
colors(255,255,255);
delay(200);
colors(0,0,0);
break;
case 'e':
colors(0,0,0);
delay(10);
colors1(0,255,0);
break;
}
}
void colors (int a, int b, int c){
for(int i=0;i<strip_count;i++){
strip.setPixelColor(i, strip.Color(a,b,c));
strip.show();
delay(1);
}
for(int i=0;i<strip2_count;i++){
strip2.setPixelColor(i, strip2.Color(a,b,c));
strip2.show();
delay(1);
}
}
void colors1 (int a, int b, int c){
for(int i=0;i<strip_count;i++){
strip.setPixelColor(i, strip.Color(a,b,c));
strip.show();
delay(1);
}
}

2:Flip and put your print in the laser cutter and align it horizontally, 90degrees to the side of your machine (see picture )Engrave the text on it

title: Portal Gun with Arduino Nano Mount

description.text:
This is a remix of Intentional3D's excellent Portal Gun:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1100601

Video of remix in action: https://youtu.be/80xivC-9lMo

I modified to fit an Arduino Nano (using emccarron's nano mounting base) and added mounts for the Adafruit 7 Segment display but the original mounting is still available as well. Also, I split the handle from the base so each could be printed on a 200 x 200 bed separately and then glued together. I've also affixed tabs to the corners of the base and top to alleviate warping if printed in solid ABS. Finally, I've counter-sunk the top screw holes for beveled machine screws.

My version is powered by dual li-poly cells via a mini dc-dc converter module set to 5V.

The Nano program is my own original work due to the different display, arduino, and rotary encoder I used. I haven't decided whether to provide the source code. The reason is because I would also have to provide schematics for wiring which would bring out the electronics and SE geeks to "correct" my evil DIY methods. I kind of think that a major part of the enjoyment for these kinds of things is the innovation to figure out things for yourself and to customize for your own idea of how it should work. At any rate, here's a list of the components I've used for this particular build:

Arduino Nano:
I used a clone that I don't even think is V3 so probably any Nano will work as long as the pins are standard, which I'd think they'd all be.

DC-DC Converter: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MQGMOKI/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Display: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GJRW0DS/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

LEDs: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01CI636JU/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Rotary Encoder: https://www.adafruit.com/product/377

Knob: https://www.adafruit.com/product/2056

Plastic LED Bevel: https://www.adafruit.com/product/2171

Batterys: This style but any similar will work (x2): https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MQE0SI4/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Ever wanted to have big teeth? Well you're in luck, with this fully printable set of chompers you'll be the talk of the town. Parts can be printed all as one or separately depending on your style. 1. Print all parts

2. Insert the ear clips into the arms of the upper jaw

3. Push the pins through the ear clips into the lower jaw

4. Slide the chin strap into the lower jaw

5. Push the teeth clips into the teeth

6. Snap the teeth onto the upper and lower jaw

7. Wrap the ear clips around your ears

8. Slide the upper jaw onto the upper jaw arms

9. Tighten the chin strap against your chin

10. Bite big things



Happy Halloween!

title: Sexy Spool Stand [SSS]
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Look at all the sexiness here!
These curves - ooooh sexy!
These threaded rods - oooooooh sexy!
This knurling on the rods - ooooooooooh aaaah sexy!

I've designed this as an experiment but it turned out really well so here it is out in the public :)

The spool rolls on 4x 608 bearings with bearing guides constraining the movement.

Threaded rods make it easy to adjust the spread out of the stand sides. In my enclosure I've used double-sided tape on one side of the stand to keep it in place but still have the ability to move the other side with the screws. The rods use a turnbuckle rule to adjust the spread out of the stand base sides - one end of the rod has a right-hand thread while the other is left-handed, the same rule applies to the base - each hole has a different direction thread.

The 85 mm rods are for spools up to 75 mm wide (most that I have fit on them), 105 mm are for spools up to 95 mm wide (e.g. Prusa-Plasty Mladec spools).

For one stand you need:
2x Base-inner
2x Base-outer
2x Rod of chosen length
4x Bearing-guide
4x 608 bearing (not included within the files lol)

Assembly instructions:

  1. Press the guides on the bearings
  2. Press the bearings on the outer piece of the base
  3. Press the inner piece of the base to the already-assembled outer piece
  4. Repeat for the other side of the stand
  5. Place one assembled side of the stand on the table with the outer piece facing down.
  6. Insert the rods, check if they screw in. If not, rotate them upside-down (they have two different-directed threads)
  7. Place the other assembled side of the stand on the rods
  8. Push the upper side down while rotating the rods towards them (two sides of the stand are brought together by rotating the rods to the inside - one to the left, the other to the right)

Printing tips below.

You can use 0% infill for the rods + 3 perimeters and print them vertically but DO USE BRIM for the rods. I've been printing with 30 outlines + 3 layers of the brim and they were holding just fine. Also, make sure you print the knurled section slow due to vibrations it revokes (30 mm/s was fine for me).

The base pieces I've printed with 75% infill + 3 perimeters to get enough strength to hold the spool.

description.text:
Here is a gearbox for a direct belt connection without the belt tensioner.

As most owners know the original gearbox has a big problem with the belt breaking.

The original design is from the_crack_fox who designed it to be CNC cut.

https://static.rcgroups.net/forums/attachments/3/9/3/8/8/6/a7856168-100-IMG_20150504_231729.jpg

I realy thank him for his design and stl file that i used to create this gearbox to be 3D printed.

Today i did the first testdrive and it's driving pretty good :-)

Must say installing it was pretty tight so i might have to move the holes that hold the motor plate just 1-2 mm. I removed the motor coverplate and after that installing it was more easy. Still some minor things i overlooked like the 2 front nuts that held the 2 screws just did not fit on because it was 2 close to the wall but with a little grinding i made it fit. I changed it in the stl file but have not printed that one yet so not sure the room i cut away is now enough.

The motorplate is held by 2 screws because the 3th hole falls in a spot where the belt is now running but it seems to hold up fine with one 2 screws in there.

I will still be making some small adjustments over time but for now this gearbox seems to be working great !

Belt i used :

6 mm 45 teeth 135 mm length.

https://nl.aliexpress.com/item/POWGE-Arc-HTD-3M-Timing-belt-C-132-135-138-141-width-6-9-15mm-Teeth/32818738308.html?spm=a2g0s.8937460.0.0.Nx8eaN

Material: ABS White and Red

title: LED Light for Anet A6 V2

description.text:
This is a second version of the LED light for Anet A6 that I made some weeks ago.
The previous design that I made worked perfectly but I didn't really liked two things.

First of all it was too bulky (I made it as small as I could but the 12V battery was occupying (and wasting) most of the space. Plus, the Anet A6 printer has the X axes rods placed side by side so this means that you can see what you are printing just through the space under the "extruder body". Since I placed the battery right there, that meant of seeing completely nothing).

Second, the way I attached it (hot glue was strong enough to held the light in place without problems but I wanted to redesign everything in order to achieve two things: find a more durable solution and an easy way to remove it without having to glue it again when I'll need it).

description.text:
Chain is made of separate chain links. I made three different chain link types:

  • with circular cross-section (needs support material )
  • with octagonal cross-section (does not need support material)
  • with square cross-section with rounded sides (does not need support material. I prefer this type.)
    Each chain link has X-shaped slot in the middle. These slots make it possible to interlink chain links into a chain. But it is also almost impossible for chain links to separate on their own. The same method is used to lock handcuffs.

I also made normal sized version for hands and smaller sized version for fingers.
Normal sized version uses M4x35mm bolt and lock-nut to assemble the handcuffs.
Small sized version uses 1.75mm filament (length about 18mm). Then you have to heat up the ends and squish them. I have used heated bed at 120°C, but you can also try other methods (soldering iron, 3d pen, hot water,...)
I have also included Fusion360 files, so anyone can change and adjust the size and shape.

Because Chain links have slots in the middle, they are not as strong as they could be. If you need stronger links, you can weld the slots with 3d pen or with friction welding with rotary tool. (After you assemble the chain.)

description.text:
Attention:
I recommend anyone to use the newer version of this model here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2615842 !

This is practically a remix of kmsd's "Customizable Better Temperature Tower" ("https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2491884). The main difference is that you can change the direction of where the highest and the lowest temperature will print: on top or on the bottom of the tower.

I also have made a second version of this remix with an overhang on the right side with a pointy cone on top of it. This is supposed to show how exact your printer prints (and cools) small pointy details. See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2615842 for version 2.

Usage example in Slic3r:

1. Generate the tower with openscad:

$ openscad tempTower.scad

Set the following variables in the openscad window to your liking: 

// temperature of the first lowest block
start_temp = 220;
// temperature of the last highest block
end_temp = 185;
// change in temperature between successively printed blocks
temp_step = 5;

Render and export the model to .stl and close openscad.

2. Generate gcode with Slic3r:

  1. Open the .stl file in Slic3r.
  2. Set layer height to 0.2mm. If not, multiply the skip and block parameters by (0.2mm/new_layer_height).
  3. Add the following to:
    "Printer Settings" -> "Custom G-code" -> "Before layer change G-code": 
    ; Layer [layer_num]

    This makes it possible for the 'setLayerTemperatur.py' script to recognize the single layers.

description.text:
Edit 2018-01-16: Upon request I uploaded an f3d file (fusion 360) for remixes. Please excuse the messy file, I am by no means an expert in Fusion 360.

This is a remix of the superpotatofudges 40mm Stock Hot End Cooling Duct. On my CR-10 using jneilliiis Radial Fan Fang the cooling duct and with it the hotend became loose after a couple of prints in my enclosure. I suppose it was the heat on the PLA and the relatively heavy Radial Fan Fang.

So with the help of donnyb99s Fusion .step Files I redesigned the whole attachment so that the fans are mounted to the carriage directly instead of the hotend. I printed it in ABS with supports and after my first 5 hour print the hotend sits perfectly firm.

I did not manage to remove the original attachment in Fusion 360 so you have to cut them with pliers (as shown in the pictures) so that you can screw the hotend to the carriage directly. Unfortunately in donnyb99s .step files the carriage was a bit different from mine. The threads which hold the hotend on my CR 10 are 3,5 mm long while the threads in his files are 5,5 mm long. For that reason I use 2 washers between the hotend and the carriage.

I used the following screws:

M4 20mm + nut on top
2x M3 10mm + washer on the left side (connection with the carriage)
2x M3 16mm for the hotend

I know some of the "washers" are copper gaskets but I used what I had lying around.

These are some parts I cooked up for a robotic pumpkin, which I entered into a contest at work. Despite spending almost 9 hours on this, between 14 entries, I only ended up getting two votes out of almost 100. I guess nobody was impressed by a robotic pumpkin. Sad face.

Anyway, this is a robotic pumpkin which runs on Arduino (I ended up using an Arduino Mega 2560 for convenience sake, but I'm sure any Arduino could work). It uses six servos (those popular clear-blue-plastic mini servos with the cross-shaped arms). I ended up running three of the servos directly from the Arduino, and then putting the other three on a 9-volt battery. The eyes have spaces for rgb LEDs, and the mouth has one hole for an Adarfuit electret microphone breakout, and one hole for a photoresistor. Combined with Arduino code, the pumpkin bot can be made to dance when it detects a clap (via the microphone), change the color of its eyes, spring into action when the lights turn on, etc. I even added an HC-05 Bluetooth module to allow for voice control from an Android phone. When you ask the pumpkin bot to give you a hug, it extends its arms and waits. Then when you place your hand in front of the photoresistor, it detects the change in lighting and then gives your arm a quick little hug.

To be honest, I couldn't get all this Arduino stuff working in time for the contest, so I just ended up making it scratch its head after being plugged in (which is what I was doing after 9 hours of labor). I might get around to creating a full fledged Instructables page complete with code and assembly instructions. But if you know the basics of Arduino, you can probably figure out how to do some pretty cool stuff without my help.

Assembling the arms is fairly intuitive (for instance, put the "servo connector" piece on the ends of each servo, put the "long connector" piece into the other end of one of the servo connectors, then put a "servo mount" piece at the end of that "long connector", etc). I used hot glue to combine each part. Just apply a liberal dab to each piece and then press it into the other piece and wait a few seconds for it to cool. Reference the pictures of the completed robot to see how the pieces go together.

To mount each arm to the pumpkin, it's necessary to drill two small holes into the pumpkin. I forget which drill bit I used, but just make a hole large enough to fit the long extension of the "root" piece, then push the root piece into the hole, and seal with hot glue. That should hold the arm.

This design could use a lot more work. Its range of motion is extremely limited, and merely angling some of the connnectors differently could help a lot. Feel free to make improvements.

Notes:

The stomach and chest pieces could benefit from a raft depending on your faith in a solid first layer. If it isn't fully secured the shapes faces of those two parts will ghost real bad on a typical cartesian with a moving bed.

Supports only from the build surface.

1 - Chest piece:
After painting mount the Nylon webbing through the 25mm slots. I used small aluminum rivets. Leave a lot of excess webbing for fitment later. Add the clips to the side straps.

2 - Switch:
After painting, assemble the switch. Route the webbing from the chest piece through the top mounting points on the switch and fit. Sew to secure in place. Add the clips to the side straps.

3 - Fitting of the chest and switch:
Once the switch and chest piece are assembled and connected to each other, go ahead and put the two on and get them into a comfortable position. Remove the excess webbing as you see fit and sew to secure.

4 - Stomach piece:
Paint and assemble, again I used rivets. Leave excess webbing and fit. Once fitted remove excess webbing as you see fit and sew to secure.

5 - Arm bands and shoulder mount:
I used 12 bands on each arm, add or remove to fit the length of the arm to the wearer. run a length of gutted 550 paracord with a knot in one end through the two holes to make a chain of them. You might choose to add a knot between each one to keep a uniform spacing. Do this until you reach the end and run the two cords through the holes in the shoulder mount. While wearing the upper half, clip the shoulder mount on and find where to tie off the cord to the shoulder mount. Remove the clip and the arms slide off.

6 - Foam locations:
Cut your foam so that you can use the shoulder mounts, the body of the switch, and the back of the chest piece as contact points.

title: Arduheater - Open source intelligent heat strip controller (dew buster)

description.text:
Arduheater is a full open source intelligent heat strip controller (dew buster).
For more information have a look a the Github repository for the project.

Motivation

Controlling dew is a big thing if you really intent to do astronomy all year around. This project will allow you to build a four channel intelligent heat strip contoller for less than 10€.

Design Goals

1. Remotely controllable

This was a very important part of the design, most heat controllers, specially the DIY ones, rely on the PWM signal for each channel being manually adjusted by means of a potentiometer. This either requires the user to be near the device tweeking it or to set it to a temperature that may be higher than the one really needed thus completely trashing efficiency. Arduheater uses a serial connection so you can use any USB-Serial-TTL dongle to adjust it's settings either you're 2 or 2000 meters away.

2. Efficient energy usage

Manual adjusted heater will either require the user to be tweeking it or they will wast more energy than necessary due to the general tendency to use a higher that required setpoint, this is valid for any PWM or bang-bang style controllers. Arduheater uses a temperature sensor (DHT22) to measure basic environmental properties such as temperature and humidity, knowing them both makes the calculation of the dew point[1] possible. Arduheater also has a temperature sensor (NTC) for each heating strip, allowing the micro-controller to have a rough estimation of the temperature the equipment is at; it will be a rough estimation because we are really interested on the lenses surface temperature but we are actually measuring the heat strip temperature, to mitigate this, Arduheater allows the user to set specific offsets per heating strip.

Arduheater uses a PID controller[2] to efficiently manage the energy so only the required amount of energy to maintain a temperature setpoint is delivered to the heating strip. This is possible due the usage of a PWM signal while driving the outputs; the delta between the environmental dew point (plus offset, i.e. setpoint) and the heating strip temperature will make the micro-controller output a PID-calculated PWM signal until this delta reaches zero. In practical terms if a 12V heating strip full on consumes 12W of power (1A) it may be possible for it to use only 1W or even less to keep the equipment above dewpoint and the power usage will be automatically updated during the night as conditions vary, so the system will be always using the least amount of power to keep the dew away.

  • [1] Dew point is that dreadful threshold at which water condensation starts to happen on the lenses/equipment.
  • [2] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) commonly used in industrial control systems.

3. Builder friendly

Using off-the-shelf components such as the Arduino Nano and easily available parts Arduheater is aimed to be build by anyone with a soldering iron and some patience, no degree in electronics required.

This snowflake decoration is meant to be made as a wall-hang or tree ornament, and can be easily be used for a multi-color, multi-material print. When I printed it, I just painted the text that is higher than the rest of the snowflake.

Note: Your retraction settings and first layer adhesion MUST be good in order to successfully print this, as it will print best with lots of retraction enabled.

1. I used the Snowflaker Generator (https://www.misha.studio/snowflaker/), exported it to an image file.
  2. Imported the image into GIMP (https://www.gimp.org) and created a path from the image. Exported that path to SVG.
  3. Opened new GIMP image, added text in a font I liked, created those as paths, exported as SVG.
  4. Imported the snowflake and text SVG's into Fusion360 and arranged them as I wanted.
  5. Extrude text and snowflake a few mm. Extrude text only a few mm.
  6. Export to STL and slice in Simplify3D.

description.text:
TealDroneChallenge

This top cover remix allows for straps/string/zip ties to cradle almost anything on top of the drone.

The purpose for this is for ultimate flight experimentation.
Enabling pilots with this drone-top luggage rack will enable endless creativity.

Features:

  • started with concept of adding a bit more material to the top of the shell and channeling it for zip ties, string, twine, etc.
  • then played with the shape of the material on top - landing on what is more of a rim that allows things to sit on top or cradle/strap them securely inside

Experimental Concepts:

  • thread straps through holes to experiment with carrying items on top
  • wrap straps around bottom of drone using top structure as a secure point to experiment with strapping objects to bottom
  • use bottom-strap configuration for dangling hooks for pickup, and nets for carrying
  • and more!

As always, be safe when flying - especially when experimenting with drone uses with this top cover.

A short screwdriver, with 7 interchangeable bits.
I've been looking for an interchangeable bit screwdriver with the metric allen wrenches and such that I use on the printer for some time now, and hadn't found it.
I found a 100 piece boxer power tool set at Fry's, for $16, which had all of the bits I needed in it, and a magnetic coupler, for use in an electric drill.
With a printed handle, and some tiny magnets, I now have exactly the screwdriver I was looking for.

Vitamins:
Â Â Â Â 1 x Magnetic coupler for using interchangeable screwdriver bits in an electric drill.
Â Â Â Â 7 x Various screwdriver bits.
Â Â Â Â 6 x Small, round rare earth magnets (Mine were 1mm thick by 3mm diameter - the magnets must be smaller than the back ends of the screwdriver bits). Print the handle. Test fit the coupler and bits - use a needle file to adjust the sockets so that the bits have a loose fit (you want them to just be able to fall out), and the coupler has a slightly tight fit (still removable, if the set screw is loosened). Insert a nut into the nut trap, and a M3 setscrew into the nut. Mix up some 2 part epoxy - I used J-B weld. Grease the back ends of the screwdriver bits, so that the epoxy you'll be using in the next step won't stick. Center each magnet on the back end of a screwdriver bit, dip the magnet in epoxy (being careful to avoid getting any on the bit) and insert the bit into its socket, magnet first. Once all 6 bits are inserted, clamp the handle lightly in a vice, so that gravity will keep all of the bits in place, and let the epoxy set overnight. Install the magnetic coupler, and tighten the set screw. After mine was finished, I decided that it could be more comfortable, so I did some finish work on it. This method of finishing assumes that it was printed in ABS. Using a temperature controlled soldering iron set to 235c, use some of your scrap ABS welding rod to fill the top of the nut trap. Using a fine rasp, or diamond grit file, round off the welding, and smooth down the extrusion ridges. Smooth everything further using fine (600 grit) sandpaper. Smooth everything even further using very fine (2200 grit) sandpaper. Pour some acetone onto a clean paper towel, and give each surface of the handle a quick wipe - just enough to give it some shine. The goal here is to have the acetone evaporate from the plastic quickly, so a wet towel is good, while a soaking towel is not. Polish the surface against your jeans - or with a polishing wheel, if you insist ;-)

I liked Justanotherguys'a approach to a filament guide. A two-piece guide can be twisted apart to thread new filament and is simple to print. I re-designed the part to work with a top-mounted LCD panel and optimized the part thickness to print rock-solid. I also added a tiny tab to ensure the guide clips in place and won't vibrate loose.

  • This part has been tested with the Original Prusa i3 Mk2S where the top frame is 40mm x 6.25mm.
  • There is 30mm clearance between the top of the Prusa frame and bottom of the guide - plenty for the OEM extruder to reach maximum 210mm calibration height without interference.
  • The guide is centered ~40mm in front of the frame and is 10mm deep for excellent alignment with the filament entry on the OEM extruder
  • The guide is 30mm wide to allow some filament flex.
  • Most of the part is 4mm thick with key sections ~6mm thick for added strength.
  • Download one file and print mirror images or download both files.

description.text:
This is an easy to print, and fully functional Alien Chestburster Halloween custom.
You just need to print the mechanism and the head, clip together, take a belt and knot a fishing line or in my case a Waxed Denteal Floss onto its place and you are ready to scare!

Here you can see how easy is that:

With double way control and old sock hiding :) (thanks to robertbl22 and cyclone for the hiding idea!)

Notes:

I printed my model from PETG, because of its higher durability. With PLA not tested yet!

0.4mm nozzle
240°C (PETG)
60°C heated bed
60% cooling fan
30 mm/s print speed
2mm Z hop when rectract. (My retraction was not the best, thats why I've got many strings, if your retraction tuned well, than the separation will be even easier than in my case, as you seen on the video)

For the mechanism I've just used 3 walls and 5 top and buttom solid layers and no infill.
With this setup took me around 4-4.5 hour to print it.

For the head I used 10% infill till the throat, to make some support for it, after that just 3 walls and 5 solid top layers has been used. With this setup it takes around 3-3.5 hours to finish.

If you have a rigid frame you can even try to print it faster.

If you have white PETG (PLA) you can make it even scarier with some paint and a white sock with some artifical blood :)

description.text:
I made a few changes to the "Mini Jack Stand" for use in my Dungeons and Dragons game. These platforms allow for 3D battles to be represented with miniatures by adjusting their height easily on the battle map. I'm using them for underwater fights; they'll work for air battles too. Or non-gaming stuff, whatever!

I swapped out the cradle at the top for a 25mm square platform, added two sizes of extender beam and a sleeve for even more height (you can add as many as you like, though it gets wobbly with more than one extension), and shrunk the whole thing a bit in order to use pieces of a bamboo BBQ skewer as a pin rather than a screw.

The original design is mostly preserved, and it's great. The holes in the inner and outer pieces are slightly different distances apart, which lets you match different holes together for very precise height levels (a bit like a Vernier Caliper or slide rule). That's not ideal for gaming though, where you only need discrete 25mm (1 inch) increments. I might change this design to accommodate that at some point. A loop of tape on the platform helps a lot with keeping the mini attached when the stand wobbles.

Enjoy!

I needed some cool light sources and couldn't find much for torches/braziers out there, so I created some! There are 3 styles, each with a model for a torch and brazier - Gothic, Stone, and Fancy (wasn't sure what to call this one - could be in a nobleman's house, dwarven, etc). These models are a PITA to paint nice but really add that extra pizzaz to the room!

Notes on printing: These are not easy to print - they are small and have a decent amount of detail. The samples in the pics were printed @ 40mm/s with .12mm layer height w/ my modded Wanhao i3 plus with good cooling. The torch shafts are so small that you cannot print them one at a time since the layers stay soft and they melt/tip over. For maximum success, print at least two at a time, so the individual layers get a chance to cool before the next layer is laid down. You need to have your retraction dialed in or you will end up with lots of stringing between the torches. I also printed the torches w/ 100% infill so they had a bit of weight to them and didn't tip over super easily, which worked out nicely.

If you like my free items on Thingiverse, check out my premium stuff for sale on Hero's Hoard, and follow EC3D on Facebook where I give away premium model sets to a follower twice a month!

description.text:
This is my design of a Cyborg Arm Cannon. It has one main cannon, and 3 smaller cannons, all of which light up. They are powered by a single 9-volt battery. The control screen was designed to hold a smartphone, to add to the robotic effect. I designed it to fit a Lumia 950 XL, but many other phones will fit it as well. All parts are to be pressed fit and glued.
I used in total about 1.5 feet of red LED strip and about 4 feet of wire. Strands of filament were used to simulate wire, and to add to the effect.
The majority of this print was printed with PLA. The Cannon Diffusers were printed with a clear PETG, and the Shields were printed with a red Translucent PETG.
Parts can be assembled for right or left arms.
Parts can also be scaled up or down for bigger or smaller arms.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm - 0.4mm

Infill:

10% - 20%

Notes:

The Mini Cannons can be printed with rafts to ensure that they stay put while printing.

Assembly

All parts should snap together fairly well. Some sanding may be required around the edges.
The holes for wire and filament may need to be widened depending on the type of wire used to assemble. The filament can be heated at one end using a heat gun or hair dryer and pressed into the holes so that the plastics fuse together.
LED's are not required, and the cannon looks just as good without them. To go a step further, an Arduino could be added, to create pulsing effects or to even control different color LED's.

Shields Part 1 and 2

The shields are printed flat. Once the print completes, you then can heat them with a hair dryer or heat gun to round the shields. I printed (2) part 1 shields, and (1) Part 2 shield. The shield can be placed where ever you want on the cannon to customize it to your liking. The get attached with an epoxy or super glue.

Control Screen and Bezel

The Control Screen gets printed with supports. Once printed, it gets glued to the Upper Arm. A smartphone can get placed inside the cutout, and the Screen Bezel gets put on over it. It is a tight fit to ensure the Phone does not go anywhere.
